## `Future` in Java

A **`Future`** represents the result of an asynchronous computation — a placeholder for a value that will be available later.

### Basic Usage
```java
ExecutorService executor = Executors.newSingleThreadExecutor();

Future<Integer> future = executor.submit(() -> {
    Thread.sleep(2000); // simulate long task
    return 42;
});

Integer result = future.get(); // blocks until result is ready
```

### Key Methods
| Method | Description |
|---|---|
| `get()` | Blocks and waits for the result |
| `get(timeout, unit)` | Waits up to a timeout |
| `isDone()` | Checks if task is complete |
| `cancel()` | Attempts to cancel the task |
| `isCancelled()` | Checks if task was cancelled |

---

## The Problem with `Future`

Basic `Future` is **limited** — you can't chain tasks, combine results, or attach callbacks without blocking.

---

## ✅ Advanced Feature: `CompletableFuture` (Java 8+)

This is the modern, powerful replacement. It supports **non-blocking**, **chainable**, and **composable** async operations.

### 1. Chaining (`.thenApply`, `.thenAccept`)
```java
CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> fetchUser(id))
    .thenApply(user -> user.getName())       // transform result
    .thenAccept(name -> System.out.println(name)); // consume result
```

### 2. Combining Two Futures (`.thenCombine`)
```java
CompletableFuture<String> cf1 = CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> "Hello");
CompletableFuture<String> cf2 = CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> "World");

cf1.thenCombine(cf2, (a, b) -> a + " " + b)
   .thenAccept(System.out::println); // "Hello World"
```

### 3. Running Multiple in Parallel (`.allOf`)
```java
CompletableFuture<Void> all = CompletableFuture.allOf(cf1, cf2, cf3);
all.join(); // wait for all to complete
```

### 4. Exception Handling (`.exceptionally`)
```java
CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> riskyOperation())
    .exceptionally(ex -> "default value on error")
    .thenAccept(System.out::println);
```

### 5. Async Variants
```java
.thenApplyAsync(...)    // runs on a different thread
.thenAcceptAsync(...)
.thenRunAsync(...)
```

---

## Quick Comparison

| Feature | `Future` | `CompletableFuture` |
|---|---|---|
| Non-blocking | ❌ | ✅ |
| Chaining | ❌ | ✅ |
| Exception handling | ❌ | ✅ |
| Combine futures | ❌ | ✅ |
| Manual completion | ❌ | ✅ |

---

**Bottom line:** Always prefer `CompletableFuture` for modern async Java code.
It gives you full control over async pipelines without blocking threads.

## Virtual Threads + CompletableFuture = ✅ Great Choice!

Yes, absolutely! This is actually a **modern best practice** introduced in **Java 21** (Virtual Threads - Project Loom).

---

## What are Virtual Threads?

Traditional threads are **OS threads** — heavy, limited (~thousands).
Virtual threads are **JVM-managed** — ultra-lightweight (millions possible).

---

## Your Code → Modernized

**Old way (Platform thread):**
```java
ExecutorService executor = Executors.newSingleThreadExecutor();
Future<Integer> future = executor.submit(() -> {
    Thread.sleep(2000);
    return 42;
});
Integer result = future.get(); // blocks the OS thread
```

**Modern way (Virtual thread + CompletableFuture):**
```java
// Java 21+ — Virtual Thread Executor
ExecutorService executor = Executors.newVirtualThreadPerTaskExecutor();

CompletableFuture<Integer> future = CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> {
    Thread.sleep(2000); // blocks virtual thread, NOT OS thread
    return 42;
}, executor);

// Non-blocking chain
future.thenAccept(result -> System.out.println("Result: " + result));
```

---

## Why This Combination Works So Well

### Virtual Threads handle the "waiting" cheaply
```java
ExecutorService vExecutor = Executors.newVirtualThreadPerTaskExecutor();

// Spawn 10,000 tasks — no problem with virtual threads!
List<CompletableFuture<Integer>> futures = IntStream.range(0, 10_000)
    .mapToObj(i -> CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> {
        Thread.sleep(1000); // each waits 1s, but no OS thread blocked
        return i * 2;
    }, vExecutor))
    .toList();

// Wait for all and collect results
CompletableFuture.allOf(futures.toArray(new CompletableFuture[0]))
    .thenRun(() -> {
        futures.stream()
               .map(CompletableFuture::join)
               .forEach(System.out::println);
    });
```

