## Real-World Example: Parallel API Calls

```java
ExecutorService vExecutor = Executors.newVirtualThreadPerTaskExecutor();

CompletableFuture<String> userFuture = CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(
    () -> fetchUser(userId), vExecutor
);

CompletableFuture<String> orderFuture = CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(
    () -> fetchOrders(userId), vExecutor
);

// Combine both results when ready
userFuture.thenCombine(orderFuture, (user, orders) -> 
    "User: " + user + ", Orders: " + orders
).thenAccept(System.out::println);
```

---

## When to Use What

| Scenario | Best Choice |
|---|---|
| Simple blocking task | Virtual Thread alone |
| Chaining / transforming results | CompletableFuture |
| Many concurrent I/O tasks | **Virtual Thread + CompletableFuture** ✅ |
| CPU-heavy parallel work | Platform threads / ForkJoinPool |

---

## Key Takeaway

> **Virtual Threads** solve the *scalability* problem (cheap blocking).
> **CompletableFuture** solves the *composition* problem (chaining, combining).
> Together → **scalable + readable async code** with no callback hell.

