## Default Behavior of CompletableFuture

When you don't pass an executor, `CompletableFuture.supplyAsync()` uses **ForkJoinPool.commonPool()** by default.

```java
// These two are IDENTICAL
CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> doWork());

CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> doWork(), ForkJoinPool.commonPool());
```

---

## So Why Pass a Virtual Thread Executor?

### The Core Difference — **Blocking Behavior**

```java
// ForkJoinPool (default) — Platform threads
CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> {
    Thread.sleep(2000); // ❌ BLOCKS a real OS thread
    return 42;           //    ForkJoinPool has ~256 threads MAX
});

// Virtual Thread Executor
CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> {
    Thread.sleep(2000); // ✅ Only blocks the virtual thread
    return 42;           //    OS thread is FREE to do other work
}, Executors.newVirtualThreadPerTaskExecutor());
```

---

## ForkJoinPool is Great But...

ForkJoinPool is designed for **CPU-bound, non-blocking** tasks (divide & conquer).

```java
// ForkJoinPool SHINES here — pure computation, no blocking
CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> {
    return heavyMathCalculation(); // no sleep, no I/O
});
```

It struggles when tasks **block** (I/O, DB calls, HTTP requests):

```java
// ❌ BAD — starves ForkJoinPool with blocking I/O
List<CompletableFuture<String>> futures = IntStream.range(0, 1000)
    .mapToObj(i -> CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> {
        return callExternalAPI(); // blocks for 500ms each
    }))
    .toList();
// ForkJoinPool only has ~N threads (N = CPU cores)
// 1000 tasks queued behind ~8 threads = massive bottleneck!
```

---

## Side by Side Proof

```java
ExecutorService virtualExec = Executors.newVirtualThreadPerTaskExecutor();

// Scenario: 1000 tasks, each blocking 1 second

// ❌ ForkJoinPool (default) — 8 core machine
// Threads available: ~8
// Time taken: ~125 seconds (1000 / 8)

CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> {
    Thread.sleep(1000);
    return "done";
}); // default pool


// ✅ Virtual Threads
// Threads available: millions
// Time taken: ~1 second (all run concurrently!)

CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> {
    Thread.sleep(1000);
    return "done";
}, virtualExec);
```

---

## The Simple Mental Model

| | ForkJoinPool | Virtual Thread Executor |
|---|---|---|
| Designed for | CPU work (no blocking) | I/O work (lots of blocking) |
| Thread count | ~CPU cores | Millions |
| Blocking impact | **Starves the pool** | No impact |
| Memory per thread | ~1MB (OS thread) | ~few KB |

---

## Bottom Line

> You **CAN** run CompletableFuture on ForkJoinPool — it works fine for **CPU-bound tasks**.
> But for **I/O, DB, HTTP calls** — pass a virtual thread executor, otherwise you're bottlenecking on a tiny pool of OS threads.

**Rule of thumb:**
- 🧮 CPU work → ForkJoinPool (default is fine)
- 🌐 I/O / blocking work → Virtual Thread Executor

Requires **Java 21+** for virtual threads (`--enable-preview` not needed anymore).

