## Direct Virtual Thread — When it's enough

```java
// Simple and clean — just run it on a virtual thread
Thread.ofVirtual().start(() -> {
    String result = callExternalAPI(); // blocking I/O
    System.out.println(result);
});
```

No `CompletableFuture`, no executor — done!

---

## So When Does Passing Virtual Executor to CF Make Sense?

**Only when you need CF's composition features AND virtual thread scalability together.**

```java
ExecutorService vExec = Executors.newVirtualThreadPerTaskExecutor();

// You NEED chaining + combining + error handling
CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> fetchUser(id), vExec)      // virtual thread
    .thenApply(user -> enrichUserData(user))                    // transform
    .thenCombine(                                               // combine
        CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> fetchOrders(id), vExec),
        (user, orders) -> buildResponse(user, orders)
    )
    .exceptionally(ex -> fallbackResponse())                    // error handle
    .thenAccept(System.out::println);
```

Here virtual threads alone **can't** give you `.thenCombine()`, `.exceptionally()` etc.

---

## Decision Tree

```
Need chaining / combining / error handling?
        |
       YES → CompletableFuture
        |         |
        |     Blocking I/O inside?
        |         |
        |        YES → Pass Virtual Thread Executor
        |        NO  → Default ForkJoinPool is fine
        |
       NO  → Just use Virtual Thread directly ✅
              Thread.ofVirtual().start(() -> { ... })
```

---

## The Real Honest Answer

| Approach | Use When |
|---|---|
| `Thread.ofVirtual().start()` | Simple fire-and-forget async task |
| `CF` with default pool | CPU work + need chaining |
| `CF` + virtual executor | I/O work + need chaining/combining |

---

## Bottom Line

> Virtual threads directly = **simplicity**
> CF + virtual executor = **composition + scalability**
>
> You only combine them when you need **both** at the same time. You're right to question it — blindly passing a virtual executor to CF without needing composition is **unnecessary complexity.**
